\begin_layout Abstract
Upstream group reciprocity also has different cognitive requirements from
 related phenomena.
 While in-group altruism and group-based downstream reciprocity require
 people to differentiate their own group from outsiders---
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

us
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

them
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

---upstream group reciprocity requires them to differentiate between different
 outgroups---between 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

them and them
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

---and to keep a mental account of outgroups' reputation.
 Upstream group reciprocity could thus provide an evolutionary basis for
 the phenomenon of outgroup stereotyping 
