\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Direct and group reciprocity
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:reciprocity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:reciprocity"

\end_inset

 presents the allocations made in the DR and GR conditions separated by
 the whether the kindness of the action of the TG partner was below the
 median or not.
 The median kindness of the senders was
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 (median transfer of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

75 out of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

150 tokens).
 The median kindness of the responders was
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 (median share returned matches the amount sent).
 The figure reveals strong direct reciprocity.
 Senders allocate less than the baseline
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

35 tokens to responders who failed to at least compensate the sender for
 the amount sent.
 Responders both allocate more than
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

35 tokens to senders who sent at least half their endowment, and less to
 those who sent less.
 These observations are confirmed by the regression analysis (see third
 column in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Table~
\backslash
ref{tab:results})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Allocations to the TG partners increase with that partner's kindness both
 for senders (
\begin_inset Formula $z=1.75,p=0.080$
\end_inset

 and for responders (
\begin_inset Formula $z=4.96,p<0.001$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Group reciprocity, however, is only observed for senders, who allocate less
 to team mates of a responder who failed to at least compensate the sender
 for the amount sent---a clear signal of bad intentions.
 Responders, on the other hand, although directly reciprocating the TG partner,
 do not systematically discriminate against team mates of a sender who sent
 little---an unkind action that does not unequivocally signals a bad intention.
 The regression analysis shows no significant effect of sender kindness
 on responder's allocation to the sender's team mates (
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.86,p=0.391$
\end_inset

).
 The responder's kindness, on the other hand, significantly increases allocation
s made to his team mates (
\begin_inset Formula $z=2.02,p<0.05$
\end_inset

).
 The estimated ratio of the group and direct reciprocity coefficients is
 0.63, implying that for every allocation dollar that the responder loses
 due to an unkind action in the TG, his team mates lose
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

63 cents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 Allocations made by to the TG partner (Direct Reciprocity) and his team
 mates (Group Reciprocity) by TG partner's kindness with
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

95% confidence intervals based on subject-level averages.
 Responders give more (less) to senders who sent more (less) then the median
 (equal to exactly half the endowment)---but do not generalize to the sender's
 team mates.
 Senders give less to responders who returned less than the median (equal
 to exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, i.e., the amount sent) and their team mates.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


