\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I'm not really comfortable with the discussion yet.
 The action/intention distinction, which is certainly plausible, is not
 completely proven by our result.
 If we make it the centrepiece of the conclusion, then we may be setting
 ourselves up to be shot down.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I know, we need a non-obvious result to talk about! One solution is to say
 that we open the door to further study of the roots of conflict.
 That's a bit weak, though.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another solution is maybe to do a second experiment.
 I had an idea: could we show that this motive actually can lead to a full-blown
 intergroup conflict?
\end_layout

\end_inset

Our results show
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
right?
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that upstream reciprocity is moderated by social boundaries.
 We distinguish between two types of reciprocity: reciprocated actions and
 reciprocated intentions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "stanca2009testing"

\end_inset

.
 People discriminate against others who harm them even if the harmful action
 does not necessarily indicate bad intentions.
 However, they only generalize to the perpetrator's  group members if the
 intentions behind the harmful actions are unequivocally bad.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This observation raises new questions regarding the nature of reciprocity
 and the role of intentions (or perceptions thereof).
 One possible interpretation stems from the distinction between intention-based
 and outcome-based motives in reciprocal behaviour 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "falk2006theory"

\end_inset

.
 Whereas intention-based reciprocity is plausibly generalisable
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
explain why.
 This is my attempt:
\end_layout

\end_inset

, i.e.
 subjects may wish to punish there is no reason to generalize outcome-based
 reciprocity to group members who don't share the outcome.
 The notion of outcome-based reciprocity is also related to that of restorative
 justice.
 A desire to equalize earnings given the TG behaviour in the experiment
 can motivate discrimination against a misbehaving TG partner, but not his
 fellow group members.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A related distinction is between actions and types.
 Stereotypical thinking can easily lead people to generalise types, whereas
 generalisation of actions is nonsensical.
 The conjecture `One member of the Blue group is a bad person, therefore
 all Blue members are bad' is plausible.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Why? Presumably if you think one member of Blue is bad, as evidenced by
 their failure to return money; and you generalize this to other members
 of Blue being bad; then you also expect those members not to return money.
 I.e.
 the second conjecture is implied by the first.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The conjecture `One member of the Blue group did not send any money, therefore
 other Blue members did not send money' is not---as the other Blue members
 did not even necessarily face the choice of how much to send as a sender.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I put this in at the intro and talked about stereotypes.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Upstream reciprocity is notoriously difficult to understand in evolutionary
 terms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "boyd1989evolution,nowak2007upstream"

\end_inset

 Group reciprocity may provide another piece of the puzzle, as it provides
 two new channels by which upstream reciprocity may evolve.
 First, group members are interdependent, especially in the small groups
 that were the norm during most of human evolutionary history.
 Punishing a perpetrator's group member therefore indirectly harms the perpetrat
or, who is dependent on his peers for, e.g., public goods provision.
 Thus, group reciprocity may bridge upstream indirect reciprocity and direct
 reciprocity.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hmm, ok I guess I need to write some theory to justify this.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Second, the evolution of indirect reciprocity acts by way of chains of reciproca
l actions, which return with some probability to the original instigator
 of the chain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nowak2007upstream"

\end_inset

.
 In a population organised in groups, such that people interact more frequently
 with their own group members, group reciprocity may increase the likelihood
 of successful reciprocal chains, facilitating the evolution of upstream
 reciprocity.
 We aim to explore these ideas in future work.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I don't think Nature/Science will go for that.
 It sounds too like tentative early research.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

